{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778260863,"nonce":"k8ewy0Vd+B2fnf5NtKA8FRHgQUU=","title":"Cost-schedule sweep (t/N)^α on Riccati and trained architectures","message":"Stage 3 in the proposed regulator-coupling / decoupling-chain programme (exploration, not committed). Depends on eval-pipeline audit (4469cae).\n\n**Question.** How much of Δv is driven by the Q-schedule shape, independent of controller class? C\u0026S use Q_t ∝ (t/N)^6 with a back-loaded terminal cliff (600 ms horizon); rlrmp training uses a uniform Q on a 2 s horizon. These are very different schedule shapes and both the direction and magnitude of Δv may be sensitive to α independently of controller parameterisation.\n\n**Analytical approach.** Add an α parameter to the Riccati solver in src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py so that Q_t ∝ (t/N)^α for α ∈ {0, 1, 2, 4, 6, 10}. Compute Riccati Δv on each α, for both C\u0026S and rlrmp regimes. Expected: monotone in α on C\u0026S regime; possibly non-monotone on rlrmp regime due to k=10 damping interaction.\n\n**Training approach.** Train a small grid (linear-regulator + GRU) at three representative α values per regime. Measure Δv. Plot Δv vs α for each architecture on a shared axis.\n\n**Discriminator.** If GRU's Δv tracks the Riccati's Δv across α, the architecture picks up schedule-induced inflation when given the chance — Gemini's \"the RNN is too smart\" claim becomes a property of the loss, not the architecture. If GRU Δv stays flat across α, Gemini's mechanism is real but possibly contingent on the specific α tried.\n\n**Success criterion.** A clean α-sweep Δv curve for both Riccati and GRU on both regimes, showing whether the two architectures track each other.\n\n**Cross-refs.** Plan §3 stage 3. C\u0026S Eq. 15 schedule. Training-methods coord c99ad9d.","files":null}]}